ESMA DEFINITION AND ROLE

ESMA (European Securities and Markets Authority) is an EU supervisory authority that does not create primary legislation but issues binding and non-binding measures that interpret and operationalize EU financial regulations.

ESMA outputs include:

Regulatory Technical Standards (RTS)
Implementing Technical Standards (ITS)
Guidelines
Q&A documents
Opinions
Supervisory briefings

Rules for application:

ESMA materials must always be applied in conjunction with an underlying EU regulation (e.g., MiFID II, MAR, EMIR)
ESMA does not independently create regulatory obligations unless explicitly empowered through EU legislation (e.g., RTS/ITS adopted by the European Commission)
ESMA guidance should be used to:
clarify ambiguous provisions
define supervisory expectations
harmonize interpretation across EU/EEA jurisdictions

Do not:

treat ESMA as a standalone regulatory regime
cite ESMA without linking it to a base EU regulation
ESMA HIERARCHY RULE

When ESMA outputs take the form of:

RTS / ITS adopted by the European Commission → treat as binding Level 2 law
Guidelines / Q&A / Opinions → treat as non-binding but authoritative supervisory interpretation

Always distinguish between binding obligations and supervisory expectations.

